Lot's of issues here.  First of all, you've got to bring order to this
situation.  It's foreign for some people to think that a financial
negotiation actually has to take place in situations like this, but
they do.  And it goes well beyond a will, although that's a piece of
the picture.

What you've got to do for the financial aspects of this is to approach
it like a business partnership in many ways.  Sit down by yourself or
with someone who's financial acumen you trust, and lay out a proposed
partnership arrangement that you think would work.  Whether it's
through combining your finances, or separating them, or an agreement
as to who owns what, and who gets what in the case of infirmity or
death, or any other issues that come up, you've got to spell it all
out.

You've also got to figure out why you're in a situation where, if he
goes, all you've got are the clothes on your back?  Is he in any
better situation?  If so, is it because he earns more than you, or
because of some other factors?  IOW, if you had never hooked up with
this guy, would you be any better off on your own and single?  If not,
then I'm not sure blaming him for the fact that this is the way it
would be if he left is fair to him unless there's an agreement between
you that you should stay home, or work part time, or otherwise inhibit
your revenue generating capabilities for the relationship, and if
that's the case, then don't do that anymore.

However, if you'd be capable of fully supporting yourself on your own,
then why are you bothered?

Anyway, once you've got the finances straightened out, then you've got
to bring order to the rest of the relationship, but again, you've got
to realize that you cannot hold him responsible for your decisions.
If you choose to stay with *him*, then realize that person he is, and
don't hold him responsible for not being who you want him to be.  Take
him for who *he* is, warts and all, or don't take him at all.

