So, things would be OK if you didn't think you'd be marrying this guy,
or having a kid with him?  Then stop thinking that you'll marry this
guy, and have a kid with him.

I don't mean to be flippant, but if you really believe that, then tell
him that you're putting the ring away, and that you've come to
conclude that you will not marry him, and that you'll keep the
relationships at that level until *you* decide that *you* need more,
and then, when that happens, *you'll* do what *you* have to do.  Tell
him that the next time he brings it up, he'd better only do so if he's
ready, willing, and able to commit to a date.

In the last couple of years of my marriage, I went through a relative
degree of emotional pain always thinking that a particular night was
*the* night that we'd make love.  Finally, I decided that I'd no
longer think that, and that under no circumstances would I ever lull
myself into believing it would happen.

IOW, I reclaimed full control over my circumstances and my life, and I
can't begin to tell you what a relief it was.  There were even a
couple of times where she offered sex, and I absolutely refused it in
no uncertain circumstances.  I did so because I knew that if I went
back once, then I'd always be hoping for the next offer, and back to
wondering if that night was *the* night.

She had always exercised some degree of control over me in that way,
but once I reclaimed control, I basically reclaimed my life.  Although
a life without sex sucked (NPI), it was wonderful compared to the
alternative, and it added to the freedom I felt to make decisions for
myself and my own life.

I had another experience in my life where my daughter's birth father
kept threatening to withhold support payments for any number of
reasons, most of which were only tangentially connected to my
daughter.  My X and I were young and needed the money, and so we ceded
all sorts of control to him over our lives that made no sense.  The
mere threat of not keeping him in a cooperative mood allowed him much
too much control over us.  Finally, I came to my senses, and decided
that no amount of money was worth it, and told him to send the money
because it was his responsibility, and that we would no longer comply
with any of his dictates or requests except to the extent that we
decided they had merit, and that we'd notify the authorities if he
didn't meet his obligations.

He didn't, and we did, and we lived the rest of the time that my
daughter lived at home with great peace of mind, at least on that
front.  (We also eventually got the money from him, but through the
state)

The moral to both of those stories is that you've got to reclaim your
life.  You can never allow anyone to dangle a carrot in front of you
and use it as a means of control, even if they have no such intent.
Reclaim control of your life by resolving that the marriage will not
happen until he sets a date, and make sure that he knows not to
mention it again until then.  Do this, and free yourself.
